{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"sourceId":"mencius","displayName":"Mencius","type":"quotes","language":"English","edition":"James Legge Translation, 1861","primaryCategory":"Philosophy & Thought","subcategory":"Confucian","audienceTags":["philosophy","ethics"],"sortPriority":45,"itemCount":31,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true,"browseOrder":"sequence","groupingLevels":["book","chapter"],"groupingLabels":["Book","Chapter"],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Mencius_English.json","version":"1.0"},"data":[{"id":"mencius-1-1-1","text":"The great man is he who does not lose his child's-heart.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 1.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":0},{"id":"mencius-1-2-2","text":"Mencius said to king Hwuy of Leang, 'Why must your Majesty use that word \"advantage?\" What I am provided with, are counsels to benevolence and righteousness, and these are my only topics.'","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 1.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1},{"id":"mencius-1-3-3","text":"If your Majesty say, 'What is to be done to advantage my kingdom?' — the great officers will say, 'What is to be done to advantage our families?' and the inferior officers and the common people will say, 'What is to be done to advantage our persons?' Superior and inferior will try to snatch this advantage the one from the other, and the kingdom will be endangered.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 1.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":2},{"id":"mencius-1-4-4","text":"Never has there been a case of a man who was not benevolent and was yet able to bring his sovereign to a state of safety and honor. Never has there been a case of a man who was benevolent, and yet neglected his parents.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 1.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":3},{"id":"mencius-1-5-5","text":"Mencius said, 'There are three things which are unfilial, and to have no posterity is the greatest of them.'","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 1.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":4},{"id":"mencius-1-6-6","text":"Mencius said, 'Virtue alone is not sufficient for the exercise of government; laws alone cannot carry themselves into practice.'","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 1.6 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"1","chapter":"6"},"sequenceIndex":5},{"id":"mencius-2-1-7","text":"Benevolence is the heart of man, and righteousness is the path of man. Pity the man who abandons the path and does not pursue it, who loses his heart and does not know to seek it again!","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 2.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":6},{"id":"mencius-2-2-8","text":"Mencius said, 'The feeling of commiseration belongs to all men; so does that of shame and dislike; and that of reverence and respect; and that of approving and disapproving. The feeling of commiseration implies the principle of benevolence; that of shame and dislike, the principle of righteousness; that of reverence and respect, the principle of propriety; and that of approving and disapproving, the principle of knowledge.'","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 2.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":7},{"id":"mencius-2-3-9","text":"The four beginnings — benevolence, righteousness, propriety, wisdom — are in us. He who knows their beginnings and develops them, is like a fire which has begun to burn, or a spring which has begun to find vent. Let them have their complete development, and they will suffice to love and protect all within the four seas.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 2.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":8},{"id":"mencius-2-4-10","text":"A man must first despise himself, and then others will despise him. A family must first destroy itself, and then others will destroy it. A kingdom must first smite itself, and then others will smite it.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 2.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":9},{"id":"mencius-2-5-11","text":"Benevolence subdues its opposite just as water subdues fire. Those, however, who nowadays practice benevolence do it as if with one cup of water they could save a whole wagon-load of fuel which was on fire.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 2.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"2","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":10},{"id":"mencius-3-1-12","text":"Mencius said, 'The way of the people is this: if they have a certain livelihood, they will have a fixed heart; if they have not a certain livelihood, they have not a fixed heart. If they have not a fixed heart, there is nothing which they will not do.'","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 3.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"3","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":11},{"id":"mencius-3-2-13","text":"Mencius said, 'Seek and you will find it; let go and you will lose it.' Thus seeking is of use in finding, for the things sought are those within yourself.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 3.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"3","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":12},{"id":"mencius-3-3-14","text":"In the individual the highest excellence is benevolence. In governing the people, the highest excellence is justice. When both are practiced, the people will prosper.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 3.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"3","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":13},{"id":"mencius-4-1-15","text":"He who attends to his greater self becomes a great man, and he who attends to his smaller self becomes a small man.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 4.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"4","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":14},{"id":"mencius-4-2-16","text":"The great man does not think beforehand of his words that they may be sincere, nor of his actions that they may be resolute; he simply speaks and does what is right.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 4.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"4","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":15},{"id":"mencius-4-3-17","text":"The disease of men is this — that they neglect their own fields, and go to weed the fields of others, and that what they require from others is great, while what they lay upon themselves is light.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 4.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"4","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":16},{"id":"mencius-4-4-18","text":"Men must be decided on what they will not do, and then they are able to act with vigor in what they ought to do.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 4.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"4","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":17},{"id":"mencius-4-5-19","text":"Mencius said, 'There is an order in the things which men seek. Some seek it in themselves, others seek it from others. Some seek it near at hand, others seek it far away.'","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 4.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"4","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":18},{"id":"mencius-5-1-20","text":"Kindly words do not enter so deeply into men as a reputation for kindness.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 5.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":19},{"id":"mencius-5-2-21","text":"When we get by our seeking and lose by our neglecting — in that case seeking is of use to getting, and the things sought are those which are in ourselves.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 5.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":20},{"id":"mencius-5-3-22","text":"Riches and honor are what men desire. They will not accept them if they are not obtained in the right way. Poverty and meanness are what men dislike. They will not avoid them if it is not in the right way to do so.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 5.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"5","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":21},{"id":"mencius-6-1-23","text":"Man's nature is naturally good, just as water naturally flows downward. There is no man without this goodness, as there is no water that does not flow downward.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 6.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"6","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":22},{"id":"mencius-6-2-24","text":"The sense of commiseration is the beginning of humanity; the sense of shame is the beginning of righteousness; the sense of courtesy is the beginning of propriety; the sense of right and wrong is the beginning of intelligence. Men have these four beginnings just as they have their four limbs.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 6.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"6","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":23},{"id":"mencius-6-3-25","text":"The trees of the Niu mountain were once beautiful. But situated in the borders of a large state, trees were cut by axes and bills — and could they retain their beauty? Still through the activity of the vegetative life day and night, and the nourishing influence of the rain and dew, they were not without buds and sprouts springing forth.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 6.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"6","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":24},{"id":"mencius-6-4-26","text":"Those who follow that part of themselves which is great are great men; those who follow that part which is little are little men.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 6.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"6","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":25},{"id":"mencius-7-1-27","text":"He who has exhausted all his mental constitution knows his nature. Knowing his nature, he knows Heaven. To preserve one's mental constitution, and nourish one's nature, is the way to serve Heaven.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 7.1 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"1"},"sequenceIndex":26},{"id":"mencius-7-2-28","text":"Mencius said, 'There is nothing better for the nurturing of the heart than to make the desires few. Here is a man whose desires are few: in some things he may not be able to keep his heart, but they will be few.'","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 7.2 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"2"},"sequenceIndex":27},{"id":"mencius-7-3-29","text":"I like fish, and I also like bear's paws. If I cannot have the two together, I will let the fish go, and take the bear's paws. So, I like life, and I also like righteousness. If I cannot keep the two together, I will let life go, and choose righteousness.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 7.3 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"3"},"sequenceIndex":28},{"id":"mencius-7-4-30","text":"If you love others and no responsive attachment is shown, look within yourself. If you rule others and your government is unsuccessful, look within yourself. If you treat others politely and they do not return your politeness, look within yourself. When we do not realize what we desire, we must turn inwards.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 7.4 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"4"},"sequenceIndex":29},{"id":"mencius-7-5-31","text":"The great man is he who retains the heart of a newborn babe.","author":"Mencius","source":"Sayings of Mencius, Book 7.5 (Legge trans.)","tags":["philosophy","confucianism","language:english","collection:mencius"],"groups":{"book":"7","chapter":"5"},"sequenceIndex":30}]}